Out of 10 days, this is all we captured some family pics and honestly, it’s enough. ❤️📸”

We spent more time living than clicking. Less posing, more playing. Less phone-in-hand, more hand-in-hand.

These  captures may be all we have on camera, but in our hearts — there are thousands of moments that will stay forever. 💫

Laughter over late breakfasts, barefoot walks, chasing the kids around, stolen glances between two tired but grateful parents…
These are the memories that matter. The ones that don’t always make it to Instagram, but live quietly in the corners of our hearts.

Cherishing this imperfectly perfect family moment with my husband and our two boys.
Because sometimes, the best memories aren’t framed — they’re felt. 🤍

Which do you prefer during family trips — tons of photos, or just soaking in the moment? Let me know below! 👇
And if you have one favorite memory from your last family trip (clicked or not!), I’d love to hear it. 💭✨

The wind rushes past your face like a wild whisper, warm and fragrant with the scent of street food, motorbike fumes, and distant incense. You’re sitting on the top deck of an open bus weaving through the neon heartbeat of Ho Chi Minh City. The sky is ink-blue, city lights flicker like stars that came down to earth, and your heart—your whole body—is buzzing.

People wave from the street, kids shout “hello!” like you’re a celebrity, and you wave back with a grin so wide it might split your face. Music bumps through the speakers—something poppy, maybe a remix of a Vietnamese hit—and it syncs perfectly with the rhythm of the night. Every turn reveals something new: a temple glowing gold, a market still alive at 9pm, a thousand scooters flowing like a river of fireflies.

You don’t know exactly where you’re going, but that doesn’t matter. This is movement, this is freedom. You’re surrounded by strangers but somehow feel entirely at home. The city’s chaos becomes a kind of harmony, and for a moment, you’re not just a tourist. You’re part of the pulse, the poetry of the street, the magic of Vietnam after dark.

And you just laugh—full, loud, free. Because this? This is joy 💁🏻😍

There was a time when that house, those walls, that laughter echoing in the hallway—it was everything. It was home. We called it “mera ghar”, our little world, where everything felt safe and full of love.

Then, as we grew older and moved out, it slowly became “mummy ka ghar”. The place we visited on weekends, during festivals, or when we needed warmth that no other place could give. The rooms still held memories, but now they were chapters we had already lived.

And then, one day, we heard it being called “nani ka ghar” by the next generation. A house that once held our childhood is now holding theirs. The cycle of love continues, just with different voices calling out to the same walls.
